This recent deforestation and burn-down of the Amazon destabilize global climate and threaten biodiversity and overall sustainability (Popkin, 2019). The Amazon being the largest rainforest in the world absorbs more greenhouse gases compared to other tropical rainforest. Cutting down the Amazon rainforest changes the global climate due to increased CO2 emissions (Anonymous, 2020; Fonseca et al., 2019; Lapola et al., 2019; Tollefson, 2010). However, it is also a threat to the local climate that is very much depending on the rainforest and the creation of precipitation due to lack of humidity brought in from the ocean (Raymond, 2005). The rainforest regulates local climate through heat absorption, evaporation, transpiration, exchange of atmospheric gases, and generation of rainfall (Stabile et al., 2019). Thus, removing rainforest alters the local climate regulation including water cycles (Fig. 2
                     ), which may change the distribution of rainfall, pattern of ocean current and global weather (Malhi et al., 2008; Raymond, 2005). This condition leads to drought and increased temperature that may contribute to the death of vulnerable trees in the forest as they are not able to adapt to the changing climate; thus, creating a cycle that may lead to further deforestation (Malhi et al., 2008). In particular, the extensive deforestation in the southern Amazon region has detained the arrival of the rainy season and reduced the plant growing season (by lessening water vapor flux to the atmosphere) (Stabile et al., 2019). Burning down the Amazon is directly affecting local and global biodiversity as rainforests in general bind CO2 from the atmosphere which counteract desertification, soil erosion, carbon footprint and climate change (Fig. 1; Tables 1, 2

                     ) (Peng et al., 2019; Popkin, 2019).
